<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=16&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;16</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=18&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;18&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_17.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_17.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>CHASE H.Q.</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>8 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
Now we're talking! We're on the home straight now, with the biggest
Speccy Christmas events of the time, and 1989 was the last of the
classic Christmases. Star of the show for me this time around was
<i>Chase HQ</i>, inevitably one of Ocean's biggies.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/0Ry2Hrh891o&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/0Ry2Hrh891o&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Christmas Adverts, 1989</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">You didn't get much in the way of Sinclair TV ads (and if I see that Spectrum+ ad one more time, I'll scream...), but this little lot from 1989 has an advert for the first lightgun bundle. <b><i>(9:57)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Ry2Hrh891o" target="0Ry2Hrh891o">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
After making a huge splash in Your Sinclair's Slots Of Fun a year
before (in which it got a great review tinged with skepticism about
how good a Speccy conversion would be as <i>OutRun</i> was still fresh in the
memory), I soon found it in the arcades when the fair came to the
small town I was growing up in.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=290 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="280" height="170"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/_64lZ6m6Foc&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/_64lZ6m6Foc&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="280" height="170"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Ghostbusters 2 Trailer</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">This suffered from sequelitus, but was one of the big movies of 1989. <b><i>(2:26)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_64lZ6m6Foc" target="_64lZ6m6Foc">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
The traveling fairground was the usual sort of thing - ropey rides,
cheap sugary foods and suspicious supervisors running the show. But it
had three saving graces: coconut ice so sweet that it makes you sick
after two bites, dodgems which cost an arm and a leg but was the most
fun you could have at the time (it was a sleepy town), and two
portacabins filled with arcade machines from <i>Pacman</i> onwards. It wasn't
the most up to date arcade - <i>Hang On</i> had the biggest draw for many
years - but after they updated their range, it was <i>Chase HQ</i> which
always had a crowd around it.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/UA5aspU6fPA&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/UA5aspU6fPA&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>SU Chase HQ Demo</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Find that Robin Reliant, then bash him to bits. <b><i>(3:54)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UA5aspU6fPA" target="UA5aspU6fPA">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
Although it came from Taito, this really was the spiritual successor
to Sega's <i>OutRun</i> as not only were the graphics smoother and sharper,
the gameplay gave you something else to do - find a particular car,
and then ram it into submission, and do it all against the clock. Each
stage also had a rather cool off-road bit which was bumpy, bendy,
dusty, and full of obstacles to smash out the way like gates, boxes
and bushes. The game was so obviously based on Miami Vice it's a
wonder that no one got sued for royalties.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=250 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d17_1989_ad9.png" target="1989_ad9.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d17_1989_ad9_small.jpg" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=175></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>The lesser-spotted <i>Chase HQ</I> double-page advert.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>Hype-wise, this had the full works - a very brief mention on the YS
news pages saying Ocean had started work on it in the Spring of 1989
with development screenshots sparsely leaked to each of the Speccy
mags in turn throughout the Summer and Autumn. You have to hand it to
Ocean's marketing division - at that time they really knew how to
tease not just the mags, but also the fans.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=250 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d17_1989_pre1.png" target="1989_pre1.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d17_1989_pre1_small.jpg" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=175></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>YS pumps up the excitement for what was to become the best ever Speccy driving game.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>When the playable demo came on the cover of the Christmas Sinclair
User together with fantastic reviews across the board, this was the
culmination of a project that would become remembered as one of the
best Spectrum games of all time, and certainly the best driving game.
<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=250 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d17_1989_rev1.png" target="1989_rev1.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d17_1989_rev1_small.jpg" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=177></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i><i>Chase HQ</I> becomes an instant classic - 96% may seem high, but it's certainly worth it.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>It wasn't just the ultra-smooth, ultra-fast arcades action that the
Spectrum conversion is remembered for, but so many nice graphical
touches between stages and on the menu screens that made this such an
admirable labour of love project which would go down as one of the
best examples of Spectrum programming available.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sadly it didn't become the Christmas #1 - it was edged out by the fad
that was Paul "<i>Gazza</i>" Gascoigne and the 3D vector novelty driving game
<i>Hard Drivin'</i>. Perhaps it's a fitting way to finish the Spectrum's
Golden Age with sheer quality losing out to pure hype, but out of the
three it is <i>Chase HQ</i> which everybody keeps playing.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR><TR><TD><IMG SRC="chocs/voxpop.png" ALIGN="LEFT"><br><IMG SRC="pngs/jimg.png" ALIGN="RIGHT"><TABLE BACKGROUND="/black7.png"><TR><TD><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#ffff00"><B><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;JIM GRIMWOOD&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><br>
<b>Over to Jim Grimwood, who runs the Your Spectrum Unofficial Archive plus manic magazine indexing which the YSRnRY finds rather useful. I think we might have caught him at an odd time...</b><br><br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Who are you and what are you up to?</font></i></b><br>
  I'm a lone lorn creetur and everythink goes contrairy with me.
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/bV3tfauw3vQ&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/bV3tfauw3vQ&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Christmas Down Under With Fry and Laurie</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Spot the Christmas connection beyond the decorations! <b><i>(4:28)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bV3tfauw3vQ" target="bV3tfauw3vQ">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite cracker gift (aside from fortune-telling fish, naturally)?</font></i></b><br>
  Anything that whistles.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Christmas Song?</font></i></b><br>
  Slade's "Merry Christmas Everybody".
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best memory of Christmases gone by?</font></i></b><br>
  That kind Mr Scrooge bringing us a huge Christmas turkey.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best Speccy Christmas memory?</font></i></b><br>
  They're all Speccy Christmases now.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Quality Street chocolate?</font></i></b><br>
  Barratt's "Milk Bottles" ... eh?! ... they're the Devil's work!
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best present ever?</font></i></b><br>
  I'm hoping that I haven't got that one yet.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Speccy game you most looked forward to?</font></i></b><br>
  Speccy Pokemon - and I'm still waiting!!
</TD></TR>
</TABLE><p>
